title: Impact of Social Determinants on Health Outcomes in Wisconsin
author: Author A. B.
summary: This research explores how core social determinants such as education, housing, and income inequality influence public health outcomes across various counties in Wisconsin. The study analyzes disparities in healthcare access and disease burden across regions.

statistical_analysis.findings: Significant correlations (p < 0.001) were found between social deprivation indices in Wisconsin counties and negative health outcomes. Counties with the lowest quartile education rates reported up to 29% higher chronic disease prevalence.

policy_implication: Recommendations for Wisconsin include investments in community-based health initiatives, housing assistance programs, and rural telehealth expansion. Improving access to education is also cited as a long-term strategy for mitigating health disparities.

statistical_analysis.findings: Significant correlations (p < 0.001) were found between social deprivation indices in New Mexico counties and negative health outcomes. Counties with the lowest quartile education rates reported up to 29% higher chronic disease prevalence.

policy_implication: Recommendations for New Mexico include investments in community-based health initiatives, housing assistance programs, and rural telehealth expansion. Improving access to education is also cited as a long-term strategy for mitigating health disparities.
references: New Mexico Annual Health Equity Report
